2019 Baywheels or Ford GoBike Data Exploration and Visualization¶

by Samhita¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

Baywheels (previously known as Ford GoBike) is a regional bike sharing system in greater San Francisco Bay Area. It is the first regional and large-scale bicycle sharing system deployed in California and on the West Coast of the United States. It was established as Bay Area Bike Share in August 2013. As of January 2018, the Bay Wheels system had over 2,600 bicycles in 262 stations across San Francisco, East Bay and San Jose. The dataset conatains the historical monthly trip data starting from 2017 to 2020. I have selected the data for the year of 2019 for my analysis.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset has 2506983 rows and 15 columns which can be logically grouped as follows:

  • Trip information: duration_sec, start_time, end_time
  • Start station info.: start_station_id, start_station_name, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude
  • End station info: end_station_id, end_station_name, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude
  • Other info.: bike_id, user_type, bike_share_for_all_trip, rental_access_method

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am interested in seeing how the trip duration varies, which type of users have more trips, which stations are more frequently used, the rental access methods and the bike share for all information for the trips. I would also like to investigate when is there a peak in the number of trips - what time of the day, which day of the week, which month of the year etc. In order to accomplish this, the start time needs to be converted from a string type to a datetime object. Also, having the trip duration in minutes might be more precise and easier to understand.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The parameters duration_sec (will add a column for duration in minutes),start_time,start_station_id,end_station_id,bike_id,user_type,bike_share_for_all_trip,rental_access_method are useful for my analysis. Also, once the start_time is transformed into a datetime object, that would add additional columns which are useful in the analysis.

# Distribution of the trips by hour in 2019
base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
sb.set_style("darkgrid")
plt.figure(figsize=[10,10])
ax=sb.countplot(data = df_clean,x = df_clean['trip_time'],color = base_color,order=hour_labels)
plt.xlabel('Start Hour of the Trip',fontsize=14);
plt.ylabel('Count',fontsize=14);
plt.title('Distribution of trips by start hour',fontsize=16);

heights=[]
for bar in ax.patches:
    heights.append(bar.get_height())

for bar in ax.patches:
    if bar.get_height() == max(heights):
        bar.set_color('r')
    else:
        bar.set_color(base_color)

It looks like the highest number of trips start at 17 i.e. 5PM followed by 8AM. This makes sense because these are typically the start and end hours for work schedule and peak traffic is expected.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

I am interested in seeing how the trip duration varies, which type of users have more trips etc. I would also like to investigate when is there a peak in the number of trips - which time of the day, which day of the week etc. In order to accomplish this, the start time needs to be converted from a string type to a datetime object. Therefore, I have added 4 new columns - 'trip_date','trip_time','trip_day' and 'trip_month' and filled these with information from the start_time column. Also, having the trip duration in minutes might be more precise and easier to understand. Therefore, I have added a new column 'duration_minutes'.

1.It looks like the highest number of trips start at 17 i.e. 5PM followed by 8AM. This makes sense because this is typically the work schedule and peak traffic is expected.
2.From the above graph, it looks like Tuesdays have the highest number of trips in 2019. The number of trips is low, over the weekends.
3.July had the highest number of trips while December had the least number of trips in 2019.
4.Of all the trips in 2019, 80.6% users were Subscribers which means they were members. The remaining 19.4% were Customers i.e. casual users.
5.It seems 89.4% users used the app for access while the remaining 10.6% users used Clipper card for access (more info. here - https://www.lyft.com/bikes/bay-wheels/clipper-card).
6.7.8% users used the "Bike share for all" affordable option while the remaining 92.2% were were regular users (more info. here - https://www.lyft.com/bikes/bay-wheels/bike-share-for-all).
7.The 2 histograms showing the distribution of the starting and end station IDs look quite similar which implies that the same stations are most frequently used as both the start and end stations for the trips.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The maximum trip duration seemed to be 15200 minutes (which is odd) from the describe() output. It looks like the trip duration is typically between 0 and 2000 minutes and it is possible that the really high values are outliers. Therefore, it looks like 99% trips are ~68 minutes approximately.There are about 24,415 rows (total rows=2506983, so only about 0.97% of data) which have values greater than 70 minutes. Therefore, I have dropped these rows.

So our suspicion about that the bikes could've been used for sightseeing etc. on weekends. seems to be true. The average trip duration seems to be constant for subscribers who could be using these for routine tasks. However, the customers could be using them on weekends for sight-seeing or for leisure because there is a significant increase in trip duration over the weekends for "Customers".

#Trip duration by start station
# set bin edges, compute centers
bin_size = 10
xbin_edges = np.arange(0, df_clean['start_station_id'].max()+bin_size, bin_size)
xbin_centers = (xbin_edges + bin_size/2)[:-1]

# compute statistics in each bin
data_xbins = pd.cut(df_clean['start_station_id'], xbin_edges, right = False, include_lowest = True)
y_means = df_clean['duration_minutes'].groupby(data_xbins).mean()
y_sems = df_clean['duration_minutes'].groupby(data_xbins).sem()

# plot the summarized data
plt.figure(figsize=[15,15])
plt.errorbar(x = xbin_centers, y = y_means, yerr = y_sems);
plt.xlabel('Start station ID',fontsize=14);
plt.ylabel('Trip Duration',fontsize=14);
plt.title('Trip Duration by start station',fontsize=16);

This is interesting because the most frequent start stations distribution was concentrated towards the left i.e. lower values of station IDs (from the Univariate analysis). However, longer trip durations seem to be concentrated towards the right here i.e. longer trips are starting from stations with higher station IDs.
